    <item>
      <title></title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/tide-sound/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 27 Jan 2022 14:57:46 -0800</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/tide-sound/</guid>
      <description>&lt;style type=&#34;text/css&#34; rel=&#34;stylesheet&#34;&gt;&#xA;body{background: #666666;}&#xA;IMG.centered {&#xA;display: block;&#xA;margin-left: auto;&#xA;margin-right: auto}&#xA;&lt;/style&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img class=&#34;centered&#34; src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/img/TideSound-web.jpg&#34; width=95%&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div style=&#34;margin: 0 auto; display: table;&#34;&gt;&#xA;&#x9;&lt;audio controls class = &#34;centered&#34; src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/Tides.wav&#34; align=&#34;center&#34;&gt;&lt;/audio&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#x9;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;ve been doing some more experiments with unusual sound sources! This one grew out of a data visualization project&amp;mdash;graphing the tides in San Francisco Bay. I realized that the tide graph had an interesting waveform to it, and I wondered what it would sound like played back at audio frequencies. The NOAA website has lists of the harmonic constituents that make up the tide graphs for a particular location. (Quick explanation if you don&amp;rsquo;t know what those are&amp;mdash;any complex waveform can be represented as a bunch of simpler waveforms added together. Harmonic constituents are the simple waveforms that can be added together to produce a tide graph.) I wrote a Csound instrument that synthesizes tide waveforms based on 11 of the most significant harmonic constituents for Alameda. The result is the sound heard here (it&amp;rsquo;s pretty quiet, so you may need to turn up your volume to hear it.) I also wrote a song based off of it, which I&amp;rsquo;m going to release on my next album.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Child Kit</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/fiction/child-kit/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 25 Jan 2022 18:09:03 -0800</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/fiction/child-kit/</guid>
      <description>&lt;style type=&#34;text/css&#34; rel=&#34;stylesheet&#34;&gt;&#xA;body{background: #6E564A;}&#xA;body{color: #EEEEEE;}&#xA;img{margin-left: 5px;}&#xA;IMG.centered {&#xA;display: block;&#xA;margin-left: 5%;&#xA;margin-right: auto}&#xA;&lt;/style&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img class = &#34;centered&#34;&#xA;src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/img/ChildKit-web.jpg&#34; width=90%&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Sarah and Nathan had decided to build a child.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;ve cleared off the table,&amp;rdquo; Nathan said.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;OK, great.&amp;rdquo; Sarah set the down the big cardboard box, and they both started taking the brightly-colored plastic pieces out of it.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;At the bottom of the box, there was a tool kit and an instruction booklet&amp;mdash;fifty pages of semi-comprehensible cave drawings. Sarah looked at the first few pages, and started snapping together the main frame. This was the easier part&amp;mdash;things would be considerably more challenging when it came time to assemble the soul.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
