    <item>
      <title>Forest Pond</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/fiction/forest-pond/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 24 Jan 2022 13:59:39 -0800</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/fiction/forest-pond/</guid>
      <description>&lt;style type=&#34;text/css&#34; rel=&#34;stylesheet&#34;&gt;&#xA;body{background: #6E564A;}&#xA;body{color: #EEEEEE;}&#xA;img{margin-left: 5px;}&#xA;IMG.centered {&#xA;display: block;&#xA;margin-left: 2.5%;&#xA;margin-right: auto}&#xA;&lt;/style&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img class=&#34;centered&#34; src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/img/ForestPond-web.jpg&#34; width=95%&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;There&amp;rsquo;s a small pond in the center of the woods, with traces of a stone foundation nearby. A frog sits on a fallen tree. A few birds fly past.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;No humans have been here for a hundred years. The closest town is Rutherford Junction, sixty miles away at the edge of the wilderness. It&amp;rsquo;s not much of a town&amp;mdash;ten houses, a general store, one paved road, a tiny park, and a very small library.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Data Visualization</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/science/data-visualization/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 01 Jan 2022 18:24:31 -0500</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/science/data-visualization/</guid>
      <description>&lt;style type=&#34;text/css&#34; rel=&#34;stylesheet&#34;&gt;&#xA;body{background: #666666;}&#xA;IMG.centered {&#xA;display: block;&#xA;margin-left: auto;&#xA;margin-right: auto}&#xA;&lt;/style&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Lately I&amp;rsquo;ve been experimenting with data visualization using Python and Matplotlib. I also recently read Rachel Carson&amp;rsquo;s classic book, &lt;em&gt;The Sea Around Us,&lt;/em&gt; which inspired me to try visualizing the tides. This page is a collection of some of my experiments. I&amp;rsquo;ll update this page whenever I finish a new visualization. Data from &lt;a href=&#34;https://tidesandcurrents.noaa.gov&#34;&gt;https://tidesandcurrents.noaa.gov&lt;/a&gt; unless otherwise noted.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img class=&#34;centered&#34; src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/img/TideSound-web.jpg&#34; width=95%&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;This is a very basic visualization&amp;mdash;just the water levels in Alameda, CA during November of 2021. This experiment had an interesting spinoff&amp;mdash;I wrote a software instrument which synthesizes the same waveform at audio frequencies, which you can learn more about &lt;a href=&#34;http://localhost:1313/tide-sound/&#34;&gt;here.&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Prejudice Reduction</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/science/psychology/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 13 Jul 2021 21:17:34 -0700</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/science/psychology/</guid>
      <description>&lt;style type=&#34;text/css&#34; rel=&#34;stylesheet&#34;&gt;&#xA;IMG.centered {&#xA;display: block;&#xA;margin-left: auto;&#xA;margin-right: auto }&#xA;&lt;/style&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;There is strong evidence that various psychological exercises can have a powerful effect on reducing prejudice. This article summarizes my understanding of some scientific papers I&amp;rsquo;ve read about the concept of prejudice reduction.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;A good introduction to the concept can be found in&lt;/em&gt; &lt;a href=&#34;https://greatergood.berkeley.edu/article/item/top_10_strategies_for_reducing_prejudice&#34;&gt;this article.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;These articles have been peer-reviewed, but science is a process of change and improvement&amp;mdash;the understanding of this subject may change with future research.&lt;/em&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
